step.reason:
\text{Recall that }\\
\qquad \sin 2\theta = 
\dfrac{2\sin\theta\cos\theta}{\underbrace{\sin^2\theta + \cos^2\theta}}_{= 1}
= \dfrac{2\tan\theta}{1+\tan^2\theta} \\
\text{Now, this looks remarkably like }\dfrac{2x}{1+x^2}.\\
\text{Hence, if we set }x = \tan\theta,\text{ then } \\
\begin{align}
  y &= \sin^{-1}\dfrac{2x}{1+x^2} = \sin^{-1}\dfrac{2\tan\theta}{1+\tan^2\theta} \\
  &= \sin^{-1}\sin 2\theta = 2\theta
\end{align}
